<h2>High snowfall in December 2017</h2>
<br><br>
In the period 9-12 December a snow event took place over parts of western- and central Europe. Along a frontal boundary (Figure 1, left panel), with a sharp gradient in temperature between the cold air in the north and moist/warm air in the south, several low pressure systems crossed the region. Significant snowfall was reported along the low-pressure tracks. In an area from the UK via the Netherlands into central Europe, 5 to 15 cm was reported in most places (even on the lower grounds of the Low Countries). Due to orographic uplift, more than 30 cm was measured in Wales and in the Low Countries, with a maximum value of 43 cm recorded in parts of the Veluwe (eastern part of the Netherlands). The storm brought heavy snowfall down to low altitudes of 20-40 cm to the southern Swiss Alps. On Monday 11th December, air traffic was disrupted at Schiphol (Amsterdam international airport) and at UK airports, including Heathrow. Disruption to road and rail services and to power supplies was also reported. In Figure 1 (right panel) there is a distinct maximum in the number of snow days over Scotland, Wales, the eastern parts of the Netherlands and northwest Germany. A high number of snow days were also experienced across the Alps.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/dec2017/analyse_2017121012.jpg"><img alt="" src="../images/dec2017/analyse_2017121012.jpg" width="250px"></a>
<a href="../images/dec2017/Numberofsnowdays.png"><img alt="" src="../images/dec2017/Numberofsnowdays.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
Figure 1: Weather map of 10th December 2017 (left) and number of snow days in December 2017 (right).
<br><br>
<h2>A series of storms over Europe in December 2017</h2>
<br><br>
The first storm of December developed in the Atlantic, west of Portugal and moved north-eastwards. On the 7th, storm Caroline (named by UK-MetOffice; „Walter“ in Germany and „Aina“ in Scandinavia) reached Ireland and the United Kingdom, moved across the North Sea to Scandinavia and dissipated there during the 11th of the month. The impacts of the storm in the UK were considerable with power outages, closed schools and bridges, delayed flights, trains and ferries, and traffic accidents. A wind gust of 42 m/s (150 km/h) was recorded at Fair Isle (Shetland) on the 7th. The storm reached south-western Norway on the evening of the 7th December, with wind gusts of 35-40 m/s (44.2 m/s at station Folgefonna, 1390 m.a.s.l., see Figure 2) and heavy rains reported. THe highest precipitation total was observed at Gullfjellet with 284.6 mm during three days (5th-7th). The wave height off Western Norway was between 9 and 14 m. According to the Meteorological Service of Norway, such a storm in Western Norway has a return period of approximately 2 years. The high precipitation amounts in combination with snow melt led to floods, closed roads and power outages. One life was lost in connection with a landslide.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/dec2017/Fx_20171207_synop_blended_public.png"><img alt="" src="../images/dec2017/Fx_20171207_synop_blended_public.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Maximum wind gust on 7 December 2017</em>
<br><br>
The second strong low pressure system of December 2017 developed on the 11th in the Bay of Biscay and was named "Ana" (by MeteoFrance; "Yves" in Germany). That low moved quickly to the north, crossed central Europe and Scandinavia and dissipated in the Barents Sea. In France the wind gusts reached locally values of 30 m/s (110 km/h) and up to 36 m/s (130 km/h) at the coasts (45 m/s on the island of Ré) and were accompanied by heavy rain and snow in the mountains (as described above). The storm reached Germany on the 12th of December with wind gusts of 40 m/s (145 km/h, 1134 m.a.s.l.) at station Brocken and 50 m/s (180 km/h, 2964 m.a.s.l.) at Zugspitze. In Switzerland wind gusts reached 53 m/s (191 km/h) in combination with foehn at station Gütsch (2283 m.a.s.l.).
<br><br>
The last storm of the year 2017 (storm Dylan, named by Met Éireann) bought strong winds and rain to Ireland and Scotland. The storm moved through Scandinavia and dissipated in the Barents Sea during the 3rd January 2018. The highest gust in Ireland was 34 m/s (124.1 km/h) reported at Malin Head. The highest official gust measured at Port Ellen (UK) was 34 m/s.
<br><br>
<h2>The weather in December 2017</h2>
<h3>Temperature deviations and extremes</h3>
<br><br>
Despite the periods of snow and ice described above, daily minumum and mean temperatures across northeast Europe were not particularly cool relative to 1981-2010 normals. Maximum daily temperatures were, however, cooler than averaged across northern England and Scotland by around 1&#176;C. The most marked temperature anomalies occurred across the Alps, and in a region stretching across the southern coasts of France and Spain. The cooler than normal temperatures across the Alps favoured the retention of snow.
